Relationship to Evaluation
The indicator creates a portfolio-level evaluation opportunity. Evaluators can use it to identify which approved projects were expected to deliver strong VfM, then investigate:

whether the original categories were robust;
whether schemes delivered the benefits and costs assumed at approval;
whether lower or higher realised value was driven by delivery, demand, price, scope, or external-context changes;
whether non-monetised impacts strengthened or weakened achieved value;
whether lessons should change future TAG assumptions or DfT category judgements.

This is where the Magenta Book VfM Evaluation and OPM King VfM Guidance can add value. They provide methods for judging actual value when the evidence is mixed and not all effects can be monetised.

Practical Implications
For the knowledge base, the DfT indicator should be coded as an appraisal transparency source rather than an evaluation source.
Useful note fields include:

reporting year and project scope;
spending included and excluded;
category distribution by approved spending;
stated limitations and uncertainty;
any explicit caveats about expected versus achieved value;
links back to the DfT VfM Framework.

This prevents a common mistake: treating an ex ante portfolio indicator as proof of ex post performance.

Lessons for VfM Evaluation
The two examples illustrate several recurring issues:

portfolio VfM can hide variation between schemes;
aggregate BCRs depend on consistent methods and comparable assumptions;
small schemes may lack strong monitoring and evaluation data;
non-monetised impacts can be important even when the headline result is monetised;
sensitivity tests are essential when evidence is partial;
expected value should not be confused with achieved value.

These lessons connect the examples to the DfT VfM Indicator, which also reports expected value at approval rather than evaluated value after delivery.

Practical Implications
For future transport VfM notes, case examples should record:

funding stream and scheme population;
whether evidence is ex ante, in-flight, or ex post;
monetised benefits and costs included in the aggregate figure;
non-monetised impacts handled outside the aggregate figure;
quality of monitoring and evaluation evidence;
sensitivity tests and assumptions;
implications for future appraisal and evaluation design.

This makes the examples useful not just as reported results, but as evidence about how transport VfM assessment works in practice.

Appraisal Scope
TAG covers several linked areas:

overview material on the transport appraisal process;
guidance for senior responsible officers and technical project managers;
appraisal units on cost-benefit analysis, costs, user and provider impacts, economic impacts, environmental impacts, social impacts, distributional impacts, and mode-specific issues;
modelling guidance on forecasting, demand modelling, assignment, calibration, validation, and uncertainty;
appraisal worksheets, databooks, software tools, supplementary guidance, and update reports.

The scope shows why transport VfM is broader than transport user benefits alone. A credible appraisal needs to account for economic, environmental, social, place-based, distributional, and uncertainty evidence where material.

Practical Implications
When integrating TAG into a VfM evidence base, useful notes should separate:

appraisal methods used to forecast value;
modelling assumptions and TAG databook values;
non-monetised effects and how they were described;
sensitivity and uncertainty analysis;
monitoring and evaluation plans;
evidence gaps that later evaluation should close.

This makes TAG useful both as a source of appraisal standards and as a map of claims that can be tested after transport interventions are delivered.

Practical Implications
For evaluators taking notes from a transport business case, the useful extraction fields are:

stage of business case and investment decision point;
strategic objectives and spending objectives;
preferred option and alternatives rejected;
VfM category, BCR, net present value, and non-monetised impacts;
key risks, sensitivities, optimism bias, and uncertainty analysis;
distributional and place-based claims;
benefits management, monitoring, and evaluation commitments.

These fields make it possible to connect DfT appraisal evidence to later process, impact, and value for money evaluation.

Risk and Uncertainty
The framework places weight on uncertainty because transport benefits and costs often depend on long-term demand, delivery risk, behavioural response, technology change, environmental assumptions, and wider economic conditions.
Good VfM advice should therefore show:

central estimates and the assumptions behind them;
sensitivity tests around material drivers of benefits and costs;
switching values where useful for showing what would need to change to alter the category;
optimism bias, cost risk, and delivery risk where relevant;
the direction and scale of non-monetised effects.

The practical implication is that uncertainty is part of the VfM judgement, not a caveat added after the result.
